Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) About Studying Dentistry in Spain
Q: What are the language requirements for study in Spain?
A: The language of instruction for many dentistry programs in Spain is Spanish. Therefore, proficiency in Spanish is essential for non-native speakers. Most universities require applicants to provide proof of language proficiency through tests such as the DELE (Diploma de Español como Lengua Extranjera).
Q: Are there any scholarships available for international students pursuing dentistry in Spain?
A: Yes, there are scholarship opportunities available for international students studying dentistry in Spain. Many universities offer scholarships based on academic merit, financial need, or specific criteria set by the institution. Additionally, students can explore external scholarship options offered by government agencies, private organizations, and international foundations.
Q: How long does it take to complete a dentistry degree in Spain?
A: The duration of a dentistry degree in Spain typically varies based on the program level. An undergraduate degree (Grado en Odontología) usually spans five to six years, while postgraduate specialization programs may take an additional two to four years to complete. Doctoral programs (Ph.D. in Dentistry) can vary in length depending on the research project and individual progress.
